#PART 1

Summary statistics for sale price by number of bedroom

bedroom_summary <- house_sales %>%
  group_by(bedrooms) %>%
  summarise(
    mean_price = mean(sale_price, na.rm = TRUE),
    median_price = median(sale_price, na.rm = TRUE),
    sd_price = sd(sale_price, na.rm = TRUE),
    count = n()
  )
print(bedroom_summary)

The summary statistics show that properties with more bedrooms tend to have higher average sale prices. This indicates that the number of bedrooms is positively associated with property value.

Boxplot of sale price by number of bedrooms

ggplot(house_sales, aes(x = factor(bedrooms), y = sale_price)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = "Sale Price by Number of Bedrooms",
       x = "Number of Bedrooms",
       y = "Sale Price") +
  theme_minimal()

# The boxplot reveals a distinct trend, indicating that properties with more bedrooms exhibit a broader price range, suggesting potential market segmentation related to property size.

Bar plot of count of properties by number of bedrooms

ggplot(bedroom_summary, aes(x = factor(bedrooms), y = count)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(title = "Count of Properties by Number of Bedrooms",
       x = "Number of Bedrooms",
       y = "Count") +
  theme_minimal()

# This plot shows that most properties typically have between 2 and 4 bedrooms, while there are fewer properties with either 1 bedroom or more than 4. It is clear that mid-sized homes are more prevalent in the market, reflecting potential buyer preferences or demand for these types of properties.

Correlation analysis

plot(house_sales$bedrooms, house_sales$sale_price)

cor(house_sales$bedrooms, house_sales$sale_price, use = "complete.obs")

#Proportion Table

By exploring the association between the number of bathrooms and the binary variable created for view quality missingness, it is clear that the absence of view quality information may correlate with the characteristics of properties. Analyzing these variables together help to understand whether the absence of view quality information is related to specific property features (such as the number of bathrooms) and can inform hypotheses about market preferences and property desirability.
